<content>
    <para id="id1171954421496">The only stable chalcogenides of aluminum are Al<sub>2</sub>S<sub>3</sub> (white), Al<sub>2</sub>Se<sub>3</sub> (grey), and Al<sub>2</sub>Te<sub>3</sub> (dark grey). They are each prepared by the direct reaction of the elements (100 °C) and hydrolyze rapidly in aqueous solution, <link target-id="eip-2444"/>. All the chalcogenides have a hexagonal ZnS structure in which <sup>2</sup>/<sub>3</sub> of the metal sites are occupied. </para>

<equation id="eip-2444"><media id="id1171956255265_media" alt="">
        <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics1-8a87.jpg" id="id1171956255265__onlineimage" width="500" print-width="4.5in"/>
      </media></equation>
    


    <para id="id1171954218656">The chalcogenides of gallium and indium are more numerous than those of aluminum, and are listed in <link target-id="id1171956313089"/> and <link target-id="id1171957659922"/> along with selected physical properties. </para>

