      <media id="id1171952767330_media" alt="">
        <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/Fig46.jpg" id="id1171952767330__onlineimage" width="250" print-width="2in"/>
      </media>
<caption>Unit cell of (a) tetragonal InS and (b) orthorhombic InS. Indium atoms are shown shaded, and the solid bonds represent the smallest cyclic structural fragment. </caption>
    </figure>




    <figure id="id1171957730843"><media id="id1171957730843_media" alt="">
        <image mime-type="image/jpg" src="../../media/graphics4-9b29.jpg" id="id1171957730843__onlineimage" width="300" print-width="2.5in"/>
      </media>

    <caption>Unit cell of tetragonal InTe. Indium atoms are shown shaded, and the solid bonds represent the [InTe<sub>2</sub>]<sub>∞</sub> chains. </caption></figure>




    <para id="id1171962433052">Further sub-chalcogenides are known for indium, e.g.; In<sub>4</sub>Se<sub>3</sub>, which contains [In(III)<sub>3</sub>Se<sub>2</sub>]<sup>5+</sup> groups (<link target-id="id1171954615299"/>). While the formally In(I) molecule In<sub>2</sub>S has been detected in the gas phase, it is actually a mixture of In and InS in the solid state.</para>

